g() {\\n            return childField;\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static class ConstructorSubject {\\n        public ConstructorSubject() {\\n        }\\n\\n        public ConstructorSubject(String value) {\\n            assertNotNull(value);\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static class FinalMethodSubject {\\n        public final String finalMethod() {\\n            return \\\"final\\\";\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static class RawListHolder {\\n        @SuppressWarnings(\\\"rawtypes\\\")\\n        private final List values = new ArrayList<String>();\\n\\n        RawListHolder() {\\n            values.add(\\\"item\\\");\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static class NewInstanceSubject {\\n        private final boolean created;\\n\\n        public NewInstanceSubject() {\\n            this.created = true;\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static class ClassForNameSubject {\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.keycloak:keycloak-client-common-synced:26.0.9/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T00-12-18-411020Z.log:2120:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring dynamic access in tests**\\n\\nI’m wondering about the dynamic access report at nativeTestCompile. It seems to use instrumentation instead of an agent, possibly due to the native image setup. I’m curious if it’s meant to report the dynamic-access call sites executed during the tests. There’s a lot to unpack here, so I’ll need to consider how instrumentation interacts with dynamic access and what that means for test execution. It’s definitely intriguing!\\n\\n**Thinking about code cleanup**\\n\\nI’m considering whether it’s okay to remove an unused file named Keycloak_client from the ReflectionsTest directory. I think it could help avoid scaffold-only clutter. It seems like using bash for file operations is encouraged, so I should do that. But I’m a bit hesitant about whether