onstructors' equals method might not return the same identity but should be based on parameters. I'm assessing several potential issues like method returns in native images.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Assessing field retrieval issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering a potential issue with `getAllDeclaredFields`, as it might not include parent fields if they aren't registered in the reflect config. That seems important to address. Also, there's a note about the reflect config; the `allDeclaredFields` format indicates reflective read/write, yet `getDeclaredFields` actually returns the fields. It's good to keep these distinctions clear in order to ensure everything works smoothly.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test class structure**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking at class and file names for tests. Helper inner class names compile to `$`, but source names don't, which raises some questions. Existing tests likely use nested classes, but to avoid needing reflect-config with `$`, might it be better to use top-level package-private helper classes in the same file? I’m unsure if that aligns with the “all top-level test classes must be public” rule. The ambiguity around this is puzzling!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating test class naming**\\\\n\\\\nI see that the classes aren’t test classes since they don’t have the `@Test` annotation. That might be fine. Should user-code-filter be included? Manual config sounds simpler, especially if we avoid `$` in class names. Refactoring could have pros, like eliminating `$` in metadata, but having multiple top-level classes in a single test file might be stylistically questionable. Java allows only one public class. Maybe using public static nested classes would help with organization, despite the rules against `$` in test names.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining code issues**\\\\n\\\\nI see some concerns with 